		分析777: "1. Definition and Normal Range of the Arterial Sclerosis Index The arterial sclerosis index (AI) is an indicator used to assess the degree of arteriosclerosis by calculating the ratio of total cholesterol (TC) to high-density lipoprotein cholesterol (HDL-C) in the blood. Under normal conditions, the AI should be less than 4. An index greater than 4 suggests a higher degree of arteriosclerosis and may increase the risk of related diseases./n2. Specific Health Risks An elevated arterial sclerosis index may lead to the following health problems:/n* Cardiovascular Diseases: Conditions such as coronary artery disease, angina pectoris, and myocardial infarction. When arteriosclerosis occurs in the coronary arteries of the heart, it can cause narrowing or blockage of the vessels, leading to insufficient blood supply to the myocardium and potentially life-threatening events./n* Cerebrovascular Diseases: Such as cerebral infarction and stroke. If arteriosclerosis affects the blood vessels in the brain, it can cause insufficient cerebral blood supply and result in a stroke./n* Renal Dysfunction: Hardening of the renal arteries may lead to a decline in kidney function and, in severe cases, renal failure./n* Fundus Lesions: Arteriosclerosis in the retinal blood vessels can impair vision and lead to retinal diseases./n* Other Complications: Such as peripheral artery disease, which can cause limb pain, numbness, and even gangrene in severe cases./n3. Causes of Increased Health Risks An elevated arterial sclerosis index can be caused by:/n* Unhealthy Lifestyle Habits: Such as a long-term high-fat diet, lack of physical activity, smoking, and excessive alcohol consumption./n* Underlying Medical Conditions: Including hypertension, hypercholesterolemia, and diabetes, which accelerate the progression of arteriosclerosis./n* Genetic Factors: Some individuals may be genetically predisposed to lipid metabolism disorders, leading to a higher arterial sclerosis index./n4. Prevention and Management Recommendations To address an elevated arterial sclerosis index, consider the following measures:/n* Adjust Your Diet: Reduce intake of high-fat and high-cholesterol foods. Increase consumption of foods rich in dietary fiber (such as vegetables, fruits, and whole grains), and include moderate amounts of unsaturated fats (such as those from fish and nuts)./n* Engage in Regular Physical Activity: Perform at least 150 minutes of moderate-intensity aerobic exercise per week, such as brisk walking, swimming, or cycling, to promote circulation and metabolism./n* Quit Smoking and Limit Alcohol Intake: Quitting smoking helps reduce vascular endothelial damage, while limiting alcohol supports blood pressure and lipid control./n* Maintain a Healthy Weight: Keep your body weight within a healthy range to avoid being overweight or obese./n* Undergo Regular Health Checkups: Monitor key indicators such as blood pressure, blood lipids, and blood glucose. Adjust lifestyle or begin medical treatment as needed./n* Medication: Under a doctor's guidance, take lipid-lowering medications (e.g., statins), antiplatelet agents (e.g., aspirin), and other relevant treatments to slow the progression of arteriosclerosis./n5. Summary An elevated arterial sclerosis index is an important risk factor for cardiovascular diseases and other related health issues. By adopting a healthy lifestyle, undergoing regular health checkups, and receiving appropriate medical interventions, you can effectively reduce these risks and protect your vascular health. If your index is found to be elevated, it is recommended to seek medical advice promptly to develop a personalized treatment plan.",
